You said:
how to switch to a new branch in github
ChatGPT said:

Here’s how you can create and/or switch to a branch from the command line in your local repo:

  1. Make sure you’re in your repo folder

    bash
    cd path/to/your/repo

  2. Fetch the latest remote branches (optional but recommended)

    bash
    git fetch

  3. List all branches

    • Local branches:

      bash
      git branch

    • Remote branches as well:

      bash
      git branch -a

  4. Switch to an existing branch

    bash
    git switch feature/your-branch-name

    (Or, if you’re on an older Git version)

    bash
    git checkout feature/your-branch-name

  5. Create and switch to a brand new branch in one step

    bash
    git switch -c feature/your-new-branch

    (Equivalent old form:)

    bash
    git checkout -b feature/your-new-branch

  6. Push your new branch up to GitHub (so it shows up in the remote)

    bash
    git push -u origin feature/your-new-branch

    The -u (or --set-upstream) makes future git push/git pull on that branch automatic.

Example: to start work on “feature/UART-printf” you’d run:

bash
git fetch
git switch -c feature/UART-printf
# (make your changes…)
git commit -am "Start UART printf feature"
git push -u origin feature/UART-printf

Now any time you want to go back to that branch:

bash
git switch feature/UART-printf
You said:
how can I increase the size of font in stm32cubeIDE
ChatGPT said:

In STM32CubeIDE (which is built on Eclipse), you can bump up the editor—and console—font sizes in two ways:

1. Quick “zoom” in the editor

  • Click in the code-editor pane.

  • Hold Ctrl and roll the mouse wheel up/down to zoom in/out.

  • Or press Ctrl + + (plus) / Ctrl + – (minus).

This only affects the current editor view, but it’s the fastest way to stretch text on the fly.

2. Permanently increase fonts via Preferences

  1. Open Preferences

    • Windows/Linux: Window → Preferences

    • macOS: STM32CubeIDE → Preferences

  2. Editor font

    1. In the tree on the left, expand General → Appearance → Colors and Fonts.

    2. Under the Basic category, select Text Font.

    3. Click Edit…, choose your preferred font size, then OK.

  3. C/C++ (and other) editors

    • Still under Colors and Fonts, look under C/C++ → C/C++ Editor Font, or under Debug → Console Font, etc., and Edit… each to your liking.

  4. Apply & Close

    • Hit Apply, then OK.

    • You may need to restart the IDE for all changes to take effect.

Tip: Increase UI scaling on high-DPI screens

If menus and icons are also tiny, you can launch CubeIDE with a DPI scaling flag. In your shortcut’s target add:

ini
--launcher.GTK_scale=1.5

(adjust “1.5” up or down), for example:

lua
"C:\ST\STM32CubeIDE\stm32cubeide.exe" --launcher.GTK_scale=1.5

This scales the entire UI—including toolbars, dialogs, and text.

You said:
what should I expect from this project when I run it
ChatGPT said:

When you download this P3_TIM1_PWM_LED build onto your Nucleo-F401RE and hit “Run,” here’s exactly what you should see:

  1. PWM-driven LED fade

    • TIM1 is driving the on-board LED (LD2) on its CH1 pin in PWM mode.

    • You’ll watch that green LED smoothly ramp its brightness up from off to full, then back down to off, over and over.

  2. Push-button trigger

    • The user button (B1 on PC13) is wired to EXTI13.

    • Whenever you press (and release) B1, it fires an interrupt, calls your HAL_GPIO_EXTI_Callback(), and runs the PWM_FadeLED() routine again—so each button press re-starts (or steps through) the fade sequence.

  3. No serial output

    • This sprint doesn’t use UART, so you won’t see anything in a terminal. Everything you’ll notice is the LED’s brightness changing.

  4. CPU still alive

    • Under the hood the SystemClock_Config has brought your clocks up to the right speeds, but there’s no low-power or sleep mode here—your CPU is simply sitting in while(1) after starting PWM.

Quick sanity checks if you don’t see the fade:

  • Make sure TIM1 CH1 is mapped to the pin where LD2 lives (on Nucleo-F401RE that’s PA8).

  • Verify in CubeMX that you’ve enabled “Start PWM” in main.c (e.g. HAL_TIM_PWM_Start(&htim1, TIM_CHANNEL_1)).

  • Confirm your EXTI for PC13 is enabled and pulling up correctly.

But in a working build you’ll simply press B1 and watch LD2 fade in and out smoothly.

ChatGPT said:

A couple of things are going on here:

1. Your “fade” code never drives the on‐board LED

On the Nucleo-F401RE the green user-LED (LD2) lives on PA5, but in CubeMX you left PA5 as a plain GPIO output and instead mapped TIM2_CH1 to PA0. Since your fade routine does

c
__HAL_TIM_SET_COMPARE(&htim2, TIM_CHANNEL_1, duty);

you’re changing Timer 2’s compare on PA0—even though nothing is wired there—so LD2 never changes brightness.

Fix:

  • In the .ioc → Pinout view, click PA5 → change its mode to TIM2_CH1 (Alternate Function).

  • Remove any “GPIO Output” assignment you had on PA5.

  • Regenerate code (Project Manager → Generate Code).

Now your PWM_Fade_Init() and __HAL_TIM_SET_COMPARE(&htim2, …) will actually modulate the LED on PA5.

2. You’re blocking inside your EXTI callback

Right now your HAL_GPIO_EXTI_Callback() calls

c
PWM_FadeLED();   // which contains `while(1){ … }`

and that entire infinite loop runs inside the interrupt. While you’re stuck in there, SysTick can’t fire (so HAL_Delay() never really advances) and the CPU never returns to normal code, so it looks like “nothing happens.”

Better pattern:

  1. Have your callback set a flag, not do the long fade inside the IRQ:

    c
    // at top of file
volatile uint8_t fade_requested = 0;

void HAL_GPIO_EXTI_Callback(uint16_t GPIO_Pin)
{
  if (GPIO_Pin == GPIO_PIN_13) {
    fade_requested = 1;
  }
}

  2. In your main loop, watch that flag and run a single fade when it goes high:

    c
    int main(void)
{
  …
  PWM_Fade_Init();   // start the timer
  while(1) {
    if (fade_requested) {
      fade_requested = 0;
      PWM_FadeLED_once();   // fades up and down *once*, then returns
    }
  }
}

  3. Change your fade routine so it only does one up-and-down pass and then returns:

    c
    void PWM_FadeLED_once(void)
{
  for (uint16_t d=0; d<=999; d+=10) {
    __HAL_TIM_SET_COMPARE(&htim2, TIM_CHANNEL_1, d);
    HAL_Delay(10);
  }
  for (uint16_t d=999; d>0; d-=10) {
    __HAL_TIM_SET_COMPARE(&htim2, TIM_CHANNEL_1, d);
    HAL_Delay(10);
  }
}

Putting it all together

  1. Reconfigure PA5 as TIM2_CH1 in CubeMX so you actually drive LD2.

  2. Regenerate code & rebuild.

  3. Refactor your EXTI callback to only set a flag.

  4. Refactor PWM_FadeLED() into a “once” version that returns.

  5. In main() loop, check that flag and call your fade function.

Once you’ve done that, when you press B1 (PC13) you’ll see LD2 on PA5 smoothly ramp up and down one time. Press again and it will repeat.

You said:
ok not pressing B1 turn on the LED, but it does not fade away
ChatGPT said:

A couple of things are happening here:

  1. Your fade‐routine still never returns
    You’re calling the original PWM_FadeLED(), which has its own

    c
    while(1) { … }

    inside it. That means as soon as you call it (from main or the callback), you never come back out — so you never notice the “down” half of the fade. Instead you’re stuck in that function’s endless loop.

  2. You need a one‐shot fade
    Rather than embed an infinite loop in your fade function, it should do exactly one up–and–down pass and then return so your main loop can keep running (and so you can reset the flag, or press the button again).

Step 1: Rewrite your fade function

In pwm_fade.c, change it to something like:

c
void PWM_FadeOnce(void)
{
  // Ramp up
  for (uint16_t d = 0; d <= 999; d += 10) {
    __HAL_TIM_SET_COMPARE(&htim2, TIM_CHANNEL_1, d);
    HAL_Delay(10);
  }
  // Ramp down
  for (uint16_t d = 999; d < 1000; d -= 10) {
    __HAL_TIM_SET_COMPARE(&htim2, TIM_CHANNEL_1, d);
    HAL_Delay(10);
  }
  // Make sure we end at 0
  __HAL_TIM_SET_COMPARE(&htim2, TIM_CHANNEL_1, 0);
}

  • Notice there’s no while(1) in there.

  • The down-loop uses d < 1000 instead of d > 0 so it won’t underflow.

And update the prototype in pwm_fade.h:

c
void PWM_FadeOnce(void);

Step 2: In main.c, call the one‐shot fade

Inside your main loop, after you start PWM:

c
/* USER CODE BEGIN 2 */
PWM_Fade_Init();    // starts TIM2 PWM, duty = whatever CCR1 was set to
/* USER CODE END 2 */

while (1)
{
  if (fade_requested)
  {
    fade_requested = 0;
    PWM_FadeOnce();
  }
}

This way:

  • On reset, fade_requested == 0 so you just sit there (and LED stays off because you’ll explicitly reset CCR1 to 0 in the fade function).

  • When you press B1, the EXTI callback sets fade_requested = 1;

  • The loop sees it, calls the one‐pass fade, then clears the flag and goes back to waiting.

Step 3: Ensure the LED really starts dark

Right after you start PWM, explicitly set the compare to zero so you don’t get whatever “leftover” duty GCCMX happened to generate:

c
PWM_Fade_Init();
__HAL_TIM_SET_COMPARE(&htim2, TIM_CHANNEL_1, 0);

Final checklist

  • ✔️ PWM_FadeOnce() has no infinite loop inside it

  • ✔️ Your main loop only calls it when fade_requested is set, and immediately clears the flag

  • ✔️ You reset CCR1 to 0 before and after each fade so the LED really goes dark in between presses

With those changes, pressing B1 will reliably make the LED ramp up, ramp down once, then sit off again until your next press.

# P3 – TIM1 PWM LED Fade

> **Project 3:** Use TIM1’s hardware PWM to smoothly fade the on-board LED and restart the effect on push-button press.

---

## 📋 Overview

This demo shows how to configure and use TIM1 on the STM32F401RE to generate a PWM signal that drives the green LED (LD2).  
A user-button (B1 on PC13) triggers an EXTI interrupt; each press requests a one-cycle fade up and fade down of the LED brightness.

---

## 🔌 Hardware

- **Board:** Nucleo-F401RE  
- **LED (LD2):** PA5, driven by TIM2_CH1 (remapped to TIM1_CH1 in CubeMX)  
- **User Button (B1):** PC13, configured as EXTI13 (falling-edge trigger)  

---

## ⚙️ Pin Configuration

| Signal        | MCU Pin | Mode                   | Pull   |
|---------------|---------|------------------------|--------|
| LD2 (Green)   | PA5     | TIM1_CH1 (Alternate)   | N/A    |
| B1 (Blue Btn) | PC13    | External Interrupt 13  | Pull-up|

*(Ensure in your `.ioc` NVIC EXTI15_10_IRQn is enabled.)*

---

## 📁 Project Structure

fw/P3_TIM1_PWM_LED/
├─ Core/
│ ├─ Inc/
│ │ └─ main.h
│ ├─ Src/
│ │ ├─ main.c
│ │ └─ stm32f4xx_it.c
│ └─ …
├─ Drivers/
│ └─ STM32F4xx_HAL_Driver/
├─ P3_TIM1_PWM_LED.ioc
└─ README.md ← (this file)

yaml

---

## 🚀 Getting Started

1. **Open** the `P3_TIM1_PWM_LED.ioc` in STM32CubeIDE.  
2. **Generate Code** (Project → Generate Code).  
3. **Build** the project (`Project → Build All`).  
4. **Flash** to your Nucleo board (`Run → Debug` or use ST-Link).  

---

## ▶️ Usage

1. After reset, the LED is off.  
2. **Press the user-button (B1)** to request a fade:  
   - LED will ramp from off → full brightness  
   - Then ramp back down → off  
3. You may press B1 again after the sequence completes to restart.

---

## 🔍 How It Works

- **`PWM_FadeInit()`** starts TIM1 PWM on CH1.  
- **`HAL_GPIO_EXTI_Callback()`** sets a `fade_requested` flag when PC13 triggers.  
- **`main()`** loop polls that flag and calls `PWM_FadeOnce()`, which performs a single up/down duty cycle using `__HAL_TIM_SET_COMPARE()` and `HAL_Delay()`.

---

## ⚠️ Notes

- The fade routine does **not** block in an interrupt— it runs in `main()` to keep SysTick working.  
- Ensure only **one** `HAL_GPIO_EXTI_Callback()` exists in your project.

You said:
please explain the code in simple words for P3 PWM TIM LED
ChatGPT said:

Here’s a high-level, plain-English walk-through of how P3 – TIM1 PWM LED Fade works:

1. Startup & Initialization (main.c)

  1. Reset & HAL init
    As soon as the chip powers up, HAL_Init() resets everything and gets the HAL libraries ready.

  2. Clock setup
    SystemClock_Config() turns on the internal oscillator, configures the PLL, and sets your CPU and bus clocks so the timer will run at the right speed.

  3. Peripheral init

    • MX_GPIO_Init() turns on the GPIO ports.

    • MX_USART2_UART_Init() brings up UART (not used here, but generated).

    • MX_TIM2_Init() (in CubeMX you mapped TIM2 → PA5 so we can drive the LED).

  4. Start PWM

    c
    PWM_Fade_Init();
__HAL_TIM_SET_COMPARE(&htim2, TIM_CHANNEL_1, 0);

    • PWM_Fade_Init() calls HAL_TIM_PWM_Start() to begin PWM on channel 1.

    • We immediately set the duty cycle to 0 so the LED stays off until you press the button.

2. Button press detection (stm32f4xx_it.c + callback)

  1. EXTI IRQ
    When you press the user-button (PC13), the hardware fires EXTI15_10_IRQHandler(), which in turn calls:

    c
    HAL_GPIO_EXTI_IRQHandler(GPIO_PIN_13);

  2. HAL callback
    The HAL library then invokes your override:

    c
    void HAL_GPIO_EXTI_Callback(uint16_t GPIO_Pin)
{
  if (GPIO_Pin == GPIO_PIN_13)
    fade_requested = 1;
}

    • That simply sets a flag (fade_requested) telling main() “hey — someone pressed the button!”

3. Main loop & one-shot fade (main.c)

c
while (1)
{
  if (fade_requested)
  {
    fade_requested = 0;     // clear the flag
    PWM_FadeOnce();         // do one fade up & down
  }
}

  • Your main() loop checks the flag over and over.

  • When it sees fade_requested == 1, it runs PWM_FadeOnce() exactly once, then goes back to waiting.

4. Fading logic (pwm_fade.c)

c
void PWM_FadeOnce(void)
{
  // Ramp brightness from off → full
  for (uint16_t d = 0; d <= 999; d += 10)
  {
    __HAL_TIM_SET_COMPARE(&htim2, TIM_CHANNEL_1, d);
    HAL_Delay(10);
  }
  // Then full → off
  for (uint16_t d = 999; d > 0; d -= 10)
  {
    __HAL_TIM_SET_COMPARE(&htim2, TIM_CHANNEL_1, d);
    HAL_Delay(10);
  }
  // Ensure completely off when done
  __HAL_TIM_SET_COMPARE(&htim2, TIM_CHANNEL_1, 0);
}

  • __HAL_TIM_SET_COMPARE changes the PWM duty cycle (how long the LED is on vs off each cycle).

  • Increasing d makes the LED brighter; decreasing makes it dimmer.

  • HAL_Delay(10) waits 10 ms between steps so you see a smooth fade.

Putting it all together

  1. Power on → LED is dark.

  2. Press B1 → Hardware interrupt → sets fade_requested.

  3. Main loop sees it → calls the fade function.

  4. LED ramps up, then down one time.

  5. Done → LED returns to dark, waiting for the next button press.

This split (IRQ just sets a flag, and the slow fade runs in main()) keeps your system responsive and lets the timer, delays, and interrupts all play nicely together.

c
#include "main.h"
#include "adc.h"
#include "tim.h"

/* USER CODE BEGIN PV */
volatile uint32_t raw_adc = 0;
/* USER CODE END PV */

int main(void)
{
  HAL_Init();
  SystemClock_Config();

  MX_GPIO_Init();
  MX_ADC1_Init();
  MX_TIM2_Init();

  // Start PWM and ADC
  HAL_TIM_PWM_Start(&htim2, TIM_CHANNEL_1);
  __HAL_TIM_SET_COMPARE(&htim2, TIM_CHANNEL_1, 0);
  HAL_ADC_Start(&hadc1);

  while (1)
  {
    // 1) Trigger & wait for one ADC conversion
    HAL_ADC_PollForConversion(&hadc1, HAL_MAX_DELAY);
    raw_adc = HAL_ADC_GetValue(&hadc1);

    // 2) Map 0–4095 → 0–1000 (match your PWM period)
    uint32_t pwm = (raw_adc * 1000) / 4095;

    // 3) Update PWM duty
    __HAL_TIM_SET_COMPARE(&htim2, TIM_CHANNEL_1, pwm);

    // 4) small delay for smoothing (optional)
    HAL_Delay(10);
  }
}

Notes

  • We start ADC in continuous mode so each PollForConversion gives the latest pot reading.

  • We map the 12-bit raw_adc (0–4095) into a 0–1000 range (assuming TIM2’s period is 1000).

  • Writing to the compare register drives the LED brightness instantly.

markdown
     ┌───────────┐
     │  POT      │
     │           │
3.3 V ─–┐     ┌───┤ GND

   WIPER─────────> PA0 (ADC1_IN0 / Arduino A0)

  • 10 kΩ linear potentiometer (any similar value 5–50 kΩ works)

  • 3× jumper wires

  • Breadboard (optional)

  • A0 → PA0 (ADC1_IN0)

  • There are nearby 3.3 V and GND pins on the same header.

  1. Power rail

    • Connect the left outer lug of the pot to 3.3 V on the Nucleo.

  2. Ground rail

  3. Wiper to ADC

    • Connect the middle lug (wiper) to PA0 (Arduino A0) on the Nucleo.
